)
</bibRefCitation>
based on genitalia and wing pattern, and this placement was confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins" box="[1084,1263,388,412]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" refString="Robbins, R. K. (1986) Evolution and identification of the New World hairstreak butterflies (Lycaenidae: Eumaeini): Eliot's Trichonis Section and Trichonis Hewitson, Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society, 40, 138 - 157." type="journal article" year="1986">
Robbins (
<number box="[1194,1255,388,412]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="1986.0">1986</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Draudt" box="[1275,1436,388,412]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" refString="Draudt, M. (1919) Theclini F. In: A. Seitz (Ed). Die Gross-Schmetterlinge der Erde, vol. 5. Die amerikanischen Tagfalter, Alfred Kernen, Stuttgart, pp. 744 - 812." type="book chapter" year="1919">
Draudt (
<number box="[1369,1427,388,412]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="1919.0">1919</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and D’Abrera (
<number box="[322,380,423,447]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="1995.0">1995</number>
) illustrated a male and a female of this species. Johnson et. al (
<number box="[1094,1152,423,447]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="1997.0">1997</number>
) created a new combination for this species, 
<taxonomicName box="[392,570,461,484]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[392,570,461,484]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">Macusia comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Robbins" box="[752,929,460,484]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" refString="Robbins, R. K. (2004) Checklist of Eumaeini. 98. Lycaenidae Theclinae, Eumaeini. 118 - 137 pp. In: Lamas, G., Checklist of Neotropical Lepidoptera. Part 4 A. Hesperioidea- Papilionoidea. Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera. J. Heppner (Ed.) Scientific Publishers, Gainesville, 439 pp." type="book chapter" year="2004">
Robbins (
<number box="[862,921,460,484]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="2004.0">2004</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
returned it to 
<taxonomicName box="[1096,1206,460,484]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1096,1206,460,484]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">Micandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, following Clench's (
<number box="[159,217,495,519]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" value="1971.0">1971</number>
) concept.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="60" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,351,1311]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,531,556]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of this species may be confused with those of 
<taxonomicName box="[955,1081,532,556]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseudolycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegides">
<emphasis box="[955,1081,532,556]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. aegides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, 
<taxonomicName box="[1211,1325,533,556]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[1211,1325,533,556]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the bluish-white ventral bands of the male, wider than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1020,1145,568,592]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseudolycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegides">
<emphasis box="[1020,1145,568,592]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. aegides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the browner ventral ground color of 
<emphasis box="[333,464,604,628]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">
<taxonomicName box="[333,460,604,628]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseudolycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegides">M. aegides</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
This species has a minute brand on the distal part of the discal cell whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[1325,1436,605,628]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,605,628]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a bluish and large androconial brand, about as large as the discal cell. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1125,1236,641,664]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[1125,1236,641,664]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[316,442,676,700]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Pseudolycaena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegides">
<emphasis box="[316,442,676,700]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. aegides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by differences on the ventral pattern as in males. Although females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1270,1346,677,700]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Thecla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ion">
<emphasis box="[1270,1346,677,700]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. ion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Micandra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="extrema">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. extrema</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown and probably very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[813,923,713,736]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[813,923,713,736]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female, I illustrate a female from Arcabuco at 
<quantity box="[151,237,748,772]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" unit="m" value="2500.0">2500 m</quantity>
where males of 
<taxonomicName box="[425,536,749,772]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Macusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comae">
<emphasis box="[425,536,749,772]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">M. comae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually collected, suggesting a high degree of confidence that the sexes are associated correctly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
